[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hi guys, this is a tutorial for&nbsp; dynamic fire VFX using Beeble Canvas. Let\'s look at the before and after. The before shot shows this man in a cave&nbsp; holding a torch, but it\'s not lit at all. And this is the after.'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Look at how everything is correctly lit with a&nbsp; blazing fire effect, and how natural the fire&nbsp;&nbsp; is moving while still maintaining the man\'s&nbsp; face, shirt, and the cave exactly the same. The second shot is a wider shot where a&nbsp; man is holding a completely empty torch. And we also want to add a&nbsp; fire that looks the same.'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This tutorial is composed of five parts. Thanks to ActionVFX for&nbsp; providing this practice footage. Let\'s dive in right away. To begin, let\'s trim this shot to 240 frames. Extract the first frame and create a&nbsp; prompt to add a fire VFX to this shot.'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But because I\'m lazy, I\'m just going&nbsp; to tell the LLM to brainstorm and&nbsp;&nbsp; give me five prompts that would&nbsp; make this shot look really good. Using Gemini, I asked it to create a&nbsp; prompt so that I can add fire to @media1,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and asked it to recommend five&nbsp; natural, realistic prompts. It\'s important to note that I asked&nbsp; it to make the prompt splittable. I did this because later, I want to use a&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Text Iterator node to split each&nbsp; text using an exclamation mark. Next, we will generate the reference image. Using the Text Iterator node, we will connect it&nbsp;&nbsp; to the Image Generator node and use&nbsp; Nano Banana 2 for image generation. After the generation, you can unpack&nbsp; this result, which will automatically&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'expand all five images that you generated&nbsp; so that you can view them at the same time. Now, just choose the image based on your&nbsp; preference. I chose image number three. So now, the next step is masking&nbsp; everything included in the white region.'

[01:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'SwitchX will lock it down so&nbsp; that all the details are kept. So, we want to include everything except the fire. I set the black region a bit larger&nbsp; in this case to give SwitchX freedom.'

[02:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And to do this, I combined three&nbsp; different masks in the Compositor node. Notice how the torch goes over the man\'s face. I\'ve excluded the man\'s face&nbsp; because if it\'s included,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'SwitchX will not generate&nbsp; fire in this specific region. Now the alpha map is ready. Let\'s connect everything&nbsp; to SwitchX: the alpha map,&nbsp;&nbsp; the source video, and the&nbsp; reference image, and run it. SwitchX will correctly add the fire&nbsp; effect while maintaining all the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'important features that you kept inside the mask. At the same time, it will relight&nbsp; the environment and the person\'s&nbsp;&nbsp; body and face so that everything&nbsp; looks like a seamless composite. You can run this exact same&nbsp; process for shot two as well.'

[02:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, the last step is to match&nbsp; the colors of the two shots. Notice how I emphasized the red color a bit more&nbsp; and made it a bit darker so that both shots match. And that\'s it.'

[02:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Thank you for watching this video. All templates are ready to be used at beeble.ai. Hope you enjoyed this. Thank you, everyone.'
